snippet.textDisplay: My car had a squeaking noise coming from the left side.  It sped up as I went faster, slowed down as I went slower, and the noise would stop completely when pressing the brake.  I took the car to my preferred shop and they said the brakes and wheel bearings were in great shape and had no idea what was causing the noise.  I took it to a shop recommended by a friend and they were also mystified, but they tried grinding the rotors to remove any impurities that may be causing it.  No luck.  I don’t see how this guy could diagnose something like my mystery squeak without even looking at the car.

snippet.textDisplay:
This guy is accidentally way ahead of the curve in some ways.

Trying to diagnose over the phone is a non-starter, you will ge just as much advice from your mechanic when you book it in. What he missed is how much diagnostics is done by computers now. Diagnostics for modern cars involves in part paying a garage to plugin your car and read the codes. Modern cars won't need to go to a garrage to do this and could just send the codes to the manufacturer when you phone them up, they charge you a few quid/bucks but can be cheaper than your mechanics first hour of time by having call centres in India or something. They can then send you to the garage to get work done. You will still be going to the garage, but potentially save money on diagnostics (not all the time) and can have parts ordered and ready to go for you to get it fixed asap.

This will become an increasingly dominant model with electric cars having less far less mechanical components where most issues will be software or electrical.

snippet.textDisplay: I’m a mechanic and I think what this guy meant was when it’s a big big job I think he meant to say go to a shop and ask these following questions so they think you know what you’re talking about and not rip you off and sell you a new engine, I think he meant to say that for jobs that you’re not able to do on your own especially for an inexperienced person...dragons were trying to make it seem like you can go to an auto parts buy something throw it on and BAM it’s brand new lol sometimes it takes special knowledge, tools, times, experience, ect...Also Debora’s comment about suing him if he gives the wrong estimate for the car lol that’s why he said go to the shop so they can know what they’re talking about lol...BUUUTTTTTT don’t get me wrong I totally disagree with the man about this invention I understand he’s trying to do a good deed but honestly if you don’t know crap about cars just take it to a shop even if you have an app telling you what to do someone inexperienced is going to be clueless about what to do or what they’re talking about...80% of my costumers are people coming to fix their car because they took matters into their own hands by using YouTube as their guidance...

snippet.textDisplay: These millionaires are not his potential customers. He should have made that clear. There are people who work on their own vehicles at home who might use a service like this once in a while.   For years I have been calling my brother in law when I am working on my machines at home. It is actually amazing how much an experienced mechanic can help an amateur (like me) over the phone. This was so well known in my family that my brother had fake pink business cards made up for him. His company was called.... Dial-a-Mech    . This even became his family nickname.
